			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=139358#p139358"><img src="./styles/prosilver/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=806">Yakk</a></strong> &raquo; May 7th, '08, 12:14 </p>

			

			<div class="content"><blockquote><div><cite>Moriquend wrote:</cite><blockquote><div><cite>Guerre5 wrote:</cite>Thanks for replys,<br /><br />That is wierd, I thought charm duration was the result of differents &quot;rolls&quot; which occurs every tick. A first roll lvl vs lvl, then MR vs MR, etc etc...<br />If you win the roll vs the creature, the charm holds. If not, it breaks. Don't remember where I readed that, it seems I misunderstood the charm duration system  <img src="./images/smilies/toothy5.gif" alt="toothy5.gif" title="toothy5.gif" /></div></blockquote><br /><br />I'm not sure that we've determined when charm duration is calculated (whether it be at the beginning or if &quot;breaK&quot; rolls are done every tick).  That aside, the part where you are off is the MR vs. MR check.  It doesn't check the mob's MR vs. your MR...it checks the mob's current MR (including debuffs) vs. the resist mod on your charm spell.</div></blockquote><br /><br />As a note, I've been looking for the parse that proves that, and haven't seen it (over the last 5 years of keeping an eye out for it!)</div>

			

