	<div id="p139366" class="post bg2">
		<div class="inner"><span class="corners-top"><span></span></span>

		<div class="postbody">
			

			<h3 ><a href="#p139366">Re: Items to increase Magic resistance ?</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=139366#p139366"><img src="./styles/prosilver/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=369">sunamae</a></strong> &raquo; May 7th, '08, 19:34 </p>

			

			<div class="content">I had been lead to believe long, long ago that it actually checks every tick when we convinced the Devs that Charisma didn't do jack for charms.  They said yes it did.  We said no it didn't. They said yes it does.  We said look at these logs.  They said hrmm that's weird.  They said hey guess what we fixed it so charisma affects charm, aren't we awesome!<br /><br />Now, that said you have to take my fuzzy recollection of 8 years ago with a grain of salt.  I was abused by Temple of Veeshan raids since then, and my brain has never been the same since.<br /><br />Programatically, it would be just as easy to calculate the charm duration at cast time and keep it server side.  It wasn't (isn't?) being sent to the client, the ShowEQ guys proved that.  I'd be willing to bet my last plat that it works however invis works (though of course it's a different algorithm.)  But, the point is, whether it figures out ahead of time when it's going to break, or does a check every tick would be identical to the player.  My gut feeling says they are doing iterations rather than plugging it into a formula or something like charisma would tend to create longer charms rather than raising the charm average (it can still break early, just not as often.)  But given enough motivation, a programmer can write an extremely convoluted algorithm to confuselate anyone.<br /><br />Sunamae<br />7th Hammer</div>

			

		</div>

		
